{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/adapters/fs.rs:2984-3024` rejects `update_task_run` whenever the caller supplies a `run_id` but the only open match is the same bead/project attempt stored without a `run_id`. That means a start recorded before the controller knew the Ralph run ID cannot be finalized later with the newly-known `run_id` or `plan_hash`, even though `started_at` is also available and the selected row could be backfilled once matched (`src/adapters/fs.rs:3186-3209`). In that recovery path the completion fails instead of updating the existing attempt.","rationale":"The bead asks for controller-driven post-run updates by bead/project and richer linkage metadata. Current matching makes that impossible for a realistic partial-information flow."},{"body":"`persist_plan` stores the canonical plan hash in the milestone snapshot (`src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:365-371`), but both `record_bead_start` and `update_task_run` ignore that state and just forward an optional caller-supplied `plan_hash` (`src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:401-446`, `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:556-568`). The FS adapter then writes `TaskRunEntry { plan_hash: None }` whenever the caller omits it (`src/adapters/fs.rs:2928-2937`, `src/adapters/fs.rs:3189-3209`). After a plan has been persisted, the system already knows which plan version is executing, so lineage can still lose the required plan linkage.","rationale":"This leaves milestone state unable to answer which plan produced an attempt even when that information is already available under the same lock."},{"body":"The change still carries a large legacy-repair layer even though the task explicitly says there is no old milestone NDJSON to migrate. Examples: named/runless fallback matching in `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:444-519`, attempt collapsing for legacy start/completion pairs in `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:521-611`, journal row rewriting in `src/adapters/fs.rs:2445-2543`, and in-place backfill helpers for missing run metadata in `src/adapters/fs.rs:2661-2733`. That reintroduces the exact backfill/repair behavior the acceptance criteria said to remove, and it makes the audit trail harder to reason about because incorrect rows are silently merged or rewritten instead of failing loudly.","rationale":"This is both a requirement miss and a significant maintainability/auditability risk for the new lineage format."}],"summary":"Milestone-record tests pass, but I found three substantive issues: completion matching cannot backfill a newly-known run ID onto an open row, plan hashes can still be dropped even when the snapshot already knows them, and the implementation still includes the legacy repair/backfill machinery the bead explicitly said to remove."}